  <div class="pixel-card mt-8 p-6 prose-retro">

A big exchange feels like a modern console dashboard. A niche exchange feels like a dedicated arcade machine. Both can be useful; they simply optimize for different players.

## Big exchange strengths

Large centralized exchanges often provide:

- stronger mainstream brand recognition;
- fiat ramps and card/bank rails;
- mobile apps and guided onboarding;
- broader support documentation;
- deeper liquidity on major assets;
- more visible compliance workflows.

These benefits matter for beginners, large positions, and users who value polished account management.

## Niche exchange strengths

TradeOgre-style venues can be more interesting when the target is:

- a smaller coin not present on big venues;
- a privacy-coin or crypto-native pair;
- a compact order-book workflow;
- low-cap discovery research;
- a user who already understands deposits, withdrawals, wallets, and limit orders.

The tradeoff is clear: less polish can mean more responsibility.

## Decision framework

Choose the route based on the job:

- **Need fiat onboarding?** Big exchange likely fits better.
- **Need obscure pair discovery?** Niche exchange may be worth checking.
- **Need high liquidity?** Verify depth before assuming.
- **Need long-term storage?** Use your own wallet, not any exchange.
- **Need support guarantees?** Do not infer them from a listing page.

